The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Nation Briefs
                                                                                                                 NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	 Gwalior, Oct. 14 (PTI): Three businessmen have been booked under the National Security Act (NSA) after a large quantity of adulterated ghee was found during raids at their establishments in Gwalior.           
	A team, compromising officials of food and revenue departments and police, raided the factories of Gyanesh Sharma, Brajesh Dubey and Naresh Nigam. The businessmen have not been arrested.                   
	 New Delhi (PTI): Taslima Nasreen came to Delhi in August but was denied permission to stay, a posting on her website says. The Indian government extended her residential permit with a condition that she must not reside in India, the post says.                   
	 Kathmandu (PTI): Two businessmen of Indian origin have been seriously injured when an unidentified group opened fire at them. Raju Prasad Gupta and Manoj Harlalka are garment traders. Two days ago, another businessman, Binod Kumar Agrawal, was shot dead by gunmen in the same town .                   
	 Mumbai (PTI): Air India has said it will operate special flights for three days between Mumbai and Nanded in Maharashtra to help Sikh devotees participate in the 300-year celebration of the holy script, Guru Granth Sahib. The three flights will fly from October 18 to 20. A one-way trip will cost Rs 2,730.                  
	 Morena (PTI): A 65-year-old self-styled godman immolated himself in public and in the presence of senior police officials at a temple in Morena in Madhya Pradesh. Avtar Das claimed he was taking samadhi for peoples welfare. The two policemen were seen sitting near the burning baba with their hands folded in reverence.                   
	 Kota (PTI): A freedom fighter died on his 100th birthday on Tuesday. Mangi Lal Bhavya had been ill for a long time. He was instrumental in setting up the Praja Mandal in the erstwhile princely state of Jhalawar in Rajasthan.
                                                                                                                           
